first state law to mandate intravenous injection of sodium pentothal in place
of gas chambers and other less humane methods. The law was further
expanded and strengthened with the Animal Protection Act of 2000.
Currently it is estimated that there are approximately 5,000
independently run animal shelters operating nationwide. Shelters have
redefined their role since the 1990's. No longer serving as an until-death
repository for strays and drop-offs, modern shelters have taken the lead in
controlling the pet population, promoting pet adoption, and studying shelter
animals health and behavior. Shelters, and shelter-like volunteer
organizations, responded to cat overpopulation with trap-neuter-release
programs that reduce feral cat populations and reduce the burden on
shelters[2].
